=> Azure Key Vault
    -> Azure Key Vault is a secure storage service to keep:
        -> Secrets (passwords, API keys, connection strings)
        -> Cryptographic keys
        -> Certificates
    -> A highly secure locker in the cloud where you store sensitive data instead of hardcoding it in your application.
    -> Problem Without Key Vault
        -> Bad Practice: String dbPassword = "mySuperSecret123";
        -> Code gets pushed to GitHub → secret exposed
        -> Anyone in team can see it. Rotation is difficult and security is high
    -> Solution with Azure Key Vault
        -> Store secrets in Key Vault instead. String dbPassword = getSecretFromKeyVault("db-password");
        -> Secret is NOT in code and access controlled via identity
        -> Centralized management

=> Core Concepts
    -> Vault: A container that holds all secrets/keys/certificates. Example: Vault Name: my-app-vault
    -> Secrets: Plain sensitive values. Example: DB password, API key, JWT secret
    -> Keys: Used for encryption/decryption. Used when You want control over cryptographic operations
    -> Certificates: Used for SSL/TLS, Secure communication
    -> Access Control
        -> Access Policies: Grant permissions manually
        -> RBAC (Recommended): Uses Azure Active Directory
        -> Example roles: Key Vault Reader, Key Vault Secrets User
    -> Real-Life Flow
        -> App runs in Azure (VM / App Service)
        -> App uses Managed Identity
        -> Identity is granted access to Key Vault
        -> App requests secret
        -> Key Vault verifies identity
        -> Returns secret securely
    -> Managed Identity: Azure_Authentication_&_Authorization
    -> Architecture Diagram
        Spring Boot App
              |
              | (Managed Identity)
              ↓
        Azure AD (Authentication)
              ↓
        Azure Key Vault
              ↓
        Secrets returned securely

=> Two Types of Key Vault Containers
    -> Azure Key Vault actually provides two different offerings:
        -> Vaults (General Purpose): This is what most people use by default. Support:
            -> Secrets
            -> Certificates
            -> Keys (both software + HSM-backed)
        -> Managed HSM(Hardware Security Module cluster) Pools:
            -> It is a Dedicated Hardware Security Module cluster, which supports:
                -> Only HSM-backed keys
                -> And doesn't support secret, certificates
                -> This is Ultra-secure, compliance-level encryption key storage

=> Azure Key Vault pillars:
    -> There are three main pillars of Azure Key Vault:
        -> Secrets Management: It store sensitive value securely.
            -> Examples: DB passwords, API keys, OAuth client secrets
            -> Benefits: No hardcoding, Access control via Azure Active Directory, Easy rotation
            -> Use case: Fetch DB password at runtime instead of hardcoding it inside application.
        -> Key Management: It is used for encryption control.
            -> Example: Encrypting customer data, Disk encryption keys
            -> You can create key, rotate key, disable key
            -> You don't store data in Key Vault, you store keys that protect data.
        -> Certificate Management: Manage SSL/TLS certificates
            -> Example: HTTPS certificates for your app
            -> Internal secure communication
            -> Features: Auto-renewal, Integration with Azure services
            -> Real world: Instead of manually uploading certificates, Key Vault manages lifecycle.

=> Service Tiers
    -> Azure Key Vault has 2 pricing tiers:
        -> Standard Tier: Uses software-based encryption. Features:
            -> Secrets
            -> Certificates
            -> Software-protected keys
            -> Suitable for normal applications, startups and in most microservices.
        -> Premium Tier: Uses Hardware Security Modules (HSM)
            -> It will add HSM-backed keys and Higher security compliance (FIPS 140-2 Level 2)
            -> It is suitable for Banking apps, Government systems, Highly sensitive data

        -> Standard vs Premium
            | Feature    | Standard | Premium   |
            | ---------- | -------- | --------- |
            | Encryption | Software | HSM 🔒    |
            | Cost       | Lower 💰 | Higher 💸 |
            | HSM Keys   | ❌       | ✅        |
            | Compliance | Basic    | High      |

=> Key Benefits of Azure Key Vault
    -> Centralized Application Secrets: Store secrets centrally and access via URI
        -> Instead of doing String dbPassword = "hardcoded123"; do String dbPassword = keyVault.getSecret("db-password");
        -> All secrets stored in one place (Key Vault), app don't store secret and just fetch when needed
        -> Your applications can securely access the information they need by using URIs. These URIs allow the applications to retrieve specific versions of a secret.
            URI: https://myvault.vault.azure.net/secrets/db-password
        -> URI alone is NOT enough — app must be authenticated via Microsoft Entra ID

    -> Securely Store Secrets and Keys: Before accessing the Key Vault, Authentication + Authorization required
        -> Step 1: Authentication: Before doing anything with Key Vault, you must authenticate
            -> Before accessing secrets: Key Vault must know WHO you are. This is done using Microsoft Entra ID
            -> There are three way to authenticate:
                -> Managed Identity (BEST PRACTICE ✅): Your app gets a built-in identity from Azure
                -> Service Principal + Certificate (NOT Recommended ⚠️): You create App identity(Service Principal) and certificate(used like password)
                    -> App use certificate to authenticate. Azure verify the certificate and access granted.
                    -> Problem here is you must store certificate and rotate manually.
                    -> Risk: If certificate expire app break and if certificate compromised, security break.
                -> Service Principal + Secret (WORST OPTION ❌): This is traditional approach(clientId + clientSecret)

                | Method           | Security | Rotation  | Recommendation |
                | ---------------- | -------- | --------- | -------------- |
                | Managed Identity | 🔒🔒🔒   | Automatic | ✅ BEST         |
                | SP + Certificate | 🔒🔒     | Manual    | ⚠️ OK          |
                | SP + Secret      | 🔒       | Hard      | ❌ Avoid        |

        -> Step 2: Authorization: What are you allowed to do. There are two ways:
            -> RBAC (Recommended): Depends on role like Admin, developer...etc.
            -> Access Policy (Old way): Direct permission inside vault. It is less flexible.
        -> Security Level:
            -> Standard → software-based
            -> Premium → HSM (hardware security)

    -> Monitor Access and Use(Logging + monitoring):
        -> You can easily track when who/what/when can accessed secret
        -> You can also see logs:
            -> Storage account → save logs
            -> Event Hub → stream logs
            -> Azure Monitor → analyze logs
        -> Real use Case: If someone accesses DB password at 2 AM → you can track it

    -> Simplified Administration(Lifecycle + scaling + replication)
        -> No need to manage HSM manually. Azure handles: Hardware security, Maintenance
        -> Automatic Scaling: If your app suddenly needs 1000 secret request/sec, Azure handle it.
        -> High Availability: Your data is Replicated automatically and available if region fails.
        -> Admin tool: You can manage Key Vault via Azure Portal, CLI, PowerShell
        -> Certificate Automation: If using SSL certificates: Auto-renewal & Auto-deployment

=> Encryption of Data in Transit
    -> “Data in transit” = Data moving between your application and Azure Key Vault
    -> Example: Your Spring Boot app → calls Key Vault → gets secret
    -> Microsoft says Key Vault enforces TLS(Transport Layer Security)
        -> Simply meaning all communication happens over secure HTTPS(App  ───(TLS/HTTPS)───> Key Vault)
        -> TLS Provides:
            | Feature        | Meaning                                    |
            | -------------- | ------------------------------------------ |
            | Authentication | You are talking to real Azure (not hacker) |
            | Privacy        | Data is encrypted 🔐                       |
            | Integrity      | Data is not modified                       |

        -> What Happens Internally
            -> TLS uses Hybrid Encryption
                -> Asymmetric encryption (RSA) → secure key exchange
                -> Symmetric encryption (AES) → fast data transfer
    -> Azure Key Vault also uses Perfect Forward Secrecy(PFS) so that each session uses unique keys, preventing decryption of past communications.
        | Cryptography Concept      | Where Used Here |
        | ------------------------- | --------------- |
        | Hybrid Encryption         | TLS internally  |
        | Asymmetric Keys           | Key exchange    |
        | Symmetric Keys            | Data encryption |
        | Integrity                 | TLS ensures     |
        | Authentication            | TLS certificate |
        | Confidentiality           | Encryption      |

=> Azure Key Vault Best Practices
    -> Use separate key vaults:
        -> Recommended to use one vault per application per environment.
        -> Example:
            -> Development
            -> Pre-Production
            -> Production
        -> This helps:
            -> Avoid sharing secrets across environments
            -> Reduce impact in case of security breach

    -> Control access to your vault:
        -> Key Vault stores sensitive and business-critical data.
        -> Access should be restricted to only authorized users and applications.
        -> Use:
            -> Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)
            -> Managed Identity (recommended)

    -> Backup:
        -> Regularly take backups of your Key Vault data.
        -> Especially during:
            -> Create
            -> Update
            -> Delete operations
        -> Helps in recovery in case of accidental loss

    -> Logging:
        -> Enable logging and monitoring for Key Vault.
        -> Track:
            -> Who accessed the vault
            -> When access happened
            -> What operation was performed
        -> Configure alerts for suspicious activity

    -> Recovery options:
        -> Enable Soft Delete:
            -> Allows recovery of deleted secrets
        -> Enable Purge Protection:
            -> Prevents permanent deletion before retention period
        -> Helps protect against accidental or malicious deletion

=> Authenticate to Azure Key Vault
    -> Authentication Overview:
        -> Azure Key Vault uses Microsoft Entra ID for authentication.
        -> It verifies the identity of a security principal before allowing access.

    -> Security Principal:
        -> A security principal is any identity that can request access to Azure resources.
        -> Types:
            -> Users:
                -> Real people with accounts in Microsoft Entra ID
            -> Groups:
                -> Collection of users
                -> Permissions assigned to group apply to all members
            -> Service Principals:
                -> Represents applications or services
                -> Acts like a user identity for apps

    -> Service Principal Creation Methods:
        -> Use Managed Identity (Recommended):
            -> Azure automatically creates and manages the service principal
            -> No need to store credentials in application
            -> Supports services like:
                -> Azure App Service
                -> Azure Functions
                -> Virtual Machines
            -> Recommended to use:
                -> System-assigned managed identity
        -> Register Application Manually:
            -> App is registered in Microsoft Entra ID
            -> Creates:
                -> Application object (global identity)
                -> Service principal (used within tenant)
            -> Requires manual credential management (secret/certificate)

    -> Authentication in Application Code:
        -> Azure Key Vault SDK uses Azure Identity library
        -> Provides unified authentication across environments
        -> Same code works for:
            -> Local development
            -> Azure deployment

        -> Supported SDKs:
            -> .NET
            -> Python
            -> Java
            -> JavaScript

    -> Authentication using REST API:
        -> Access token must be passed in HTTP header:
            Authorization: Bearer <access_token>
        -> Example:
            -> PUT /keys/MYKEY?api-version=<api_version>
            -> Authorization: Bearer <access_token>
        -> If token is missing or invalid:
            -> HTTP 401 Unauthorized error is returned
        -> Response includes WWW-Authenticate header:
            -> Contains:
                -> authorization:
                    -> OAuth2 authorization endpoint to get token
                -> resource:
                    -> Target resource (https://vault.azure.net)

    -> Key Points:
        -> Authentication proves "Who you are"
        -> Authorization (RBAC/Policy) defines "What you can access"
        -> Managed Identity is best practice for secure and seamless authentication

=> Azure App Configuration Service
    -> Overview:
        -> Azure App Configuration is a service used to centrally manage application settings and feature flags.
        -> It helps manage configurations for distributed applications running in cloud environments.
        -> Avoids issues caused by scattered configuration across multiple services.

    -> Purpose:
        -> Store all application settings in one centralized place
        -> Secure and control access to configuration data

    -> Key Benefits:
        -> Fully managed service:
            -> Can be set up quickly without infrastructure management
        -> Flexible key representation:
            -> Supports different formats and mappings for configuration keys
        -> Labeling (Tagging):
            -> Assign labels to differentiate configurations
            -> Example:
                -> dev, test, prod
        -> Point-in-time replay:
            -> Retrieve configuration from a previous state/version
        -> Feature flag management:
            -> Enable/disable features without code change
            -> Dedicated UI available
        -> Configuration comparison:
            -> Compare different configurations across environments
        -> Security:
            -> Supports Managed Identity for secure access
            -> Encryption:
                -> At rest
                -> In transit
        -> Integration:
            -> Works with popular frameworks and languages

    -> Relationship with Azure Key Vault:
        -> App Configuration:
            -> Stores application settings (non-sensitive)
        -> Azure Key Vault:
            -> Stores secrets (passwords, keys, certificates)
        -> Both services are used together in real-world applications

    -> Use Cases:
        -> Centralized configuration management:
            -> Manage settings across environments and regions
        -> Dynamic configuration updates:
            -> Change settings without redeploying application
        -> Feature flags:
            -> Enable or disable features in real-time

    -> How to Use:
        -> Connect using client libraries based on language/framework:
            -> .NET / ASP.NET Core:
                -> App Configuration provider for .NET
            -> Java (Spring):
                -> App Configuration provider for Spring Cloud
            -> JavaScript / Node.js:
                -> App Configuration provider for JavaScript
            -> Python:
                -> App Configuration provider for Python
            -> Others:
                -> Use REST API

    -> Key Points:
        -> App Configuration manages settings, not secrets
        -> Use with Azure Key Vault for complete configuration + secret management
        -> Supports dynamic updates and feature toggling

-> Azure App Configuration: Key-Value Pairs

    -> Overview:
        -> Azure App Configuration stores configuration data as key-value pairs.
        -> Key = identifier (name)
        -> Value = actual configuration data

    -> Keys:
        -> Keys act as identifiers to store and retrieve values.
        -> Hierarchical Structure:
            -> Keys can be organized using delimiters like:
                -> :
                -> /
            -> Example:
                -> AppName:Service1:ApiEndpoint
                -> AppName:Service2:ApiEndpoint
        -> Important Points:
            -> App Configuration treats keys as a single string (no parsing of hierarchy)
            -> Keys are case-sensitive:
                -> app1 ≠ App1
            -> Keys are Unicode strings
        -> Restrictions:
            -> Cannot use characters:
                -> *
                -> ,
                -> \
            -> To use reserved characters:
                -> Escape using \
        -> Size Limit:
            -> Total size of key + value + attributes ≤ 10,000 characters

    -> Key Naming Design:
        -> Two approaches:
            -> Flat structure
            -> Hierarchical structure (recommended)
        -> Advantages of hierarchical:
            -> Easier readability
            -> Better organization
            -> Easy querying using patterns

    -> Labels:
        -> Labels differentiate key-values with the same key
        -> Example:
            -> Key = AppName:DbEndpoint, Label = Test
            -> Key = AppName:DbEndpoint, Label = Production
        -> Default:
            -> No label = \0 (null label)
        -> Use Cases:
            -> Environment separation:
                -> Dev / Test / Prod
            -> Versioning
            -> Feature variations

    -> Versioning:
        -> App Configuration does NOT provide automatic versioning
        -> Use labels to manage versions
        -> Example:
            -> Label = v1.0
            -> Label = v2.0
            -> Label = commit-id

    -> Query Key-Values:
        -> Each key-value is uniquely identified by:
            -> Key + Label
        -> Query using patterns:
            -> Retrieve group of configurations based on hierarchy

    -> Values:
        -> Values are Unicode strings
        -> Can store any type of configuration data
        -> Content Type (Optional):
            -> Metadata describing value format
            -> Example:
                -> JSON
                -> XML

    -> Security:
        -> Data is encrypted:
            -> At rest
            -> In transit
        -> Important:
            -> App Configuration is NOT for secrets
            -> Use Azure Key Vault for sensitive data

    -> Key Points:
        -> Key = Name, Value = Data
        -> Labels = Differentiation (env, version)
        -> Hierarchical keys = better organization
        -> Not a replacement for Key Vault

=> Manage Application Features (Feature Flags)
    -> Overview:
        -> Feature management allows enabling/disabling features without redeploying code.
        -> Uses feature flags (toggles) to control feature behavior dynamically.

    -> Feature Flags:
        -> Definition: A feature flag is a boolean variable (ON/OFF).
                       The feature flag also has an associated code block.
                       The state of the feature flag triggers whether the code block runs or not.
        -> Behavior:
            -> ON (true)  → Feature code executes
            -> OFF (false) → Feature code is skipped
        -> Example:
            -> if (featureFlag) {
                   // run feature
               }
        -> Can be:
            -> Static:
                -> featureFlag = true
            -> Dynamic:
                -> featureFlag = isBetaUser()

    -> Core Components:
        -> Application:
            -> Contains feature flag logic in code
        -> Feature Flag Repository:
            -> Stores feature flags and their states
            -> Example:
                -> Azure App Configuration (central storage)

    -> Feature Manager:
        -> Responsible for managing feature flags lifecycle
        -> Provides:
            -> Evaluation of flags
            -> Caching
            -> Dynamic updates

    -> Filters:
        -> Definition: Rules to decide when a feature should be enabled
        -> Examples:
            -> User group (beta users)
            -> Device type (mobile/desktop)
            -> Location (India/US)
            -> Time-based (only during sale)
        -> Behavior:
            -> Multiple filters can be applied
            -> Evaluated in order
            -> First matching filter → feature ON
            -> If none match → feature OFF

    -> Feature Flag Declaration:
        -> Each feature flag contains:
            -> Name
            -> Filters (optional)
        -> Example (JSON):
            -> FeatureA:
                -> true (always ON)
            -> FeatureB:
                -> false (always OFF)
            -> FeatureC:
                -> EnabledFor:
                    -> Percentage = 50%
                        -> Enabled for 50% users

    -> Feature Flag Repository:
        -> Feature flags should be externalized (not hardcoded)
        -> Stored in centralized system
        -> Benefits:
            -> No code change required
            -> No redeployment needed
            -> Real-time control
        -> Azure App Configuration:
            -> Acts as central repository
            -> Manage flags easily
            -> Integrated with applications via SDK

    -> Key Points:
        -> Feature flags = control feature rollout dynamically
        -> Enables A/B testing, gradual rollout
        -> Decouples deployment from release
        -> Use App Configuration for centralized management

=> Securing Application Configuration Data (Azure App Configuration)

    -> Overview:
        -> Azure App Configuration provides multiple ways to secure configuration data.
        -> Key methods:
            -> Customer-Managed Keys (CMK)
            -> Private Endpoints
            -> Managed Identity

    -> Encrypt Configuration Data using Customer-Managed Keys (CMK):
        -> Default Behavior:
            -> Azure App Configuration encrypts data at rest using AES-256 encryption.
            -> Encryption key is:
                -> Automatically created
                -> Managed by Microsoft

        -> What is Customer-Managed Key (CMK)?
            -> Instead of Microsoft managing the encryption key, you manage the key yourself using Azure Key Vault.

        -> Why use CMK?
            -> More control over encryption keys
            -> Can rotate keys manually
            -> Can revoke access if needed
            -> Required in high-security environments

    -> How CMK Works (Step-by-Step Flow):

        -> Step 1:
            -> Azure App Configuration has its own internal encryption key.

        -> Step 2:
            -> You enable Customer-Managed Key feature.

        -> Step 3:
            -> A Managed Identity is assigned to App Configuration.

        -> Step 4:
            -> Managed Identity authenticates with Microsoft Entra ID.

        -> Step 5:
            -> App Configuration calls Azure Key Vault.

        -> Step 6:
            -> Key Vault performs "Key Wrapping":
                -> Encrypts (wraps) the App Configuration encryption key

        -> Step 7:
            -> Wrapped (encrypted) key is stored securely

        -> Step 8:
            -> When needed:
                -> Key Vault "unwraps" (decrypts) the key
                -> App Configuration uses it to encrypt/decrypt data

        -> Step 9:
            -> Unwrapped key is cached for 1 hour
            -> After that:
                -> It is refreshed again from Key Vault

    -> Key Concepts:

        -> AES-256 Encryption:
            -> Strong encryption algorithm used for securing data at rest

        -> Key Wrapping:
            -> Encrypting one key using another key

        -> Managed Identity:
            -> Secure identity used to access Key Vault without credentials

        -> Key Vault:
            -> Stores and manages encryption keys securely

    -> Customer-Managed Key (CMK) Flow Diagram
                         ┌──────────────────────────────┐
                         │   Your Application           │
                         └─────────────┬────────────────┘
                                       │
                                       │ (1) Store / Read Config
                                       ▼
                         ┌──────────────────────────────┐
                         │ Azure App Configuration      │
                         │                              │
                         │  (2) Encrypt Data using      │
                         │      Internal Key (Key A)    │
                         └─────────────┬────────────────┘
                                       │
                                       │ (3) Needs to secure Key A
                                       ▼
                         ┌──────────────────────────────┐
                         │ Managed Identity             │
                         │ (No username/password)       │
                         └─────────────┬────────────────┘
                                       │
                                       │ (4) Authenticate
                                       ▼
                ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────┐
                │ Microsoft Entra ID                           │
                │ (Identity Verification)                      │
                └─────────────┬────────────────────────────────┘
                              │
                              │ (5) Access Token
                              ▼
                ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────┐
                │ Azure Key Vault                              │
                │                                              │
                │  (6) Key B (Customer Managed Key)            │
                │                                              │
                │  Wrap Key A  → Encrypt Key A                 │
                │  Unwrap Key A → Decrypt Key A                │
                └─────────────┬────────────────────────────────┘
                              │
                              │ (7) Wrapped Key A stored
                              ▼
                ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────┐
                │ Azure App Configuration                      │
                │                                              │
                │  (8) Unwrapped Key cached (1 hour)           │
                │  (9) Used to encrypt/decrypt data            │
                └──────────────────────────────────────────────┘
        -> Step:
           Step 1 → Data encrypted using Key A
           Step 2 → Key A protected using Key B (CMK in Key Vault) or Key A is wrapped (encrypted) using Key B (Customer-Managed Key in Key Vault)
           Step 3 → Managed Identity used to access Key Vault

    -> Important Points:

        -> Data is always encrypted at rest
        -> CMK gives control over encryption keys
        -> Managed Identity ensures secure communication
        -> Key Vault is used for key management
        -> Key is cached temporarily for performance

    -> Simple Flow Summary:

        -> Data → Encrypted using internal key
        -> Internal key → Encrypted (wrapped) using Key Vault key
        -> Managed Identity → Used to access Key Vault securely

=> Enable Customer-Managed Key (CMK) in Azure App Configuration

    -> Overview:
        -> Customer-Managed Key (CMK) allows you to control encryption keys using Azure Key Vault.
        -> Azure App Configuration uses this key to secure its internal encryption key.

    -> Required Components:

        -> Azure App Configuration:
            -> Must be Standard tier
            -> CMK is not supported in Free tier
        -> Azure Key Vault:
            -> Must have:
                -> Soft-delete enabled
                -> Purge protection enabled
            -> Ensures keys cannot be permanently deleted accidentally
        -> Key inside Key Vault:
            -> Type:
                -> RSA or RSA-HSM
            -> Conditions:
                -> Key must be enabled
                -> Key must not be expired
                -> Must support operations:
                    -> Wrap Key
                    -> Unwrap Key

    -> Configuration Steps:

        -> Step 1: Assign Managed Identity
            -> Enable Managed Identity for App Configuration instance
            -> This identity will be used to access Key Vault securely
        -> Step 2: Grant Permissions in Key Vault
            -> Provide access to the Managed Identity
            -> Required permissions:
                -> GET:
                    -> To read key metadata
                -> WRAP:
                    -> To encrypt (wrap) the internal key
                -> UNWRAP:
                    -> To decrypt (unwrap) the internal key

    -> Flow After Setup:
        -> App Configuration → Uses Managed Identity
        -> Managed Identity → Authenticates via Entra ID
        -> Access Key Vault → Uses Key (CMK)
        -> Wrap/Unwrap internal encryption key
        -> Encrypt/Decrypt configuration data

    -> Key Points:
        -> CMK gives full control over encryption keys
        -> Managed Identity avoids storing credentials
        -> Key Vault enforces strong security (soft delete + purge protection)
        -> Proper permissions are mandatory for key operations

=> Use Private Endpoints for Azure App Configuration

    -> Overview:
        -> Private Endpoint allows secure access to Azure App Configuration over a private network.
        -> It avoids exposing the service to the public internet.

    -> What is Private Endpoint?
        -> A private endpoint is a private IP address from your Virtual Network (VNet)
        -> It is assigned to your App Configuration instance
        -> Communication happens using Azure's internal network (Microsoft backbone)

    -> How it Works:

        -> Step 1:
            -> Private Endpoint is created inside your Virtual Network

        -> Step 2:
            -> App Configuration gets a private IP address

        -> Step 3:
            -> Application connects using this private IP

        -> Step 4:
            -> Traffic flows:
                -> Within VNet
                -> Through Microsoft backbone network
                -> Not over public internet

    -> Security Benefits:

        -> Block Public Access:
            -> Disable public endpoint
            -> Only allow private network access

        -> Data Protection:
            -> Traffic never goes to internet
            -> Reduced risk of interception

        -> Network Isolation:
            -> Service becomes accessible only inside your VNet

    -> Connectivity Options:

        -> From Azure Resources:
            -> Apps inside same VNet can directly access App Configuration

        -> From On-Premises:
            -> Connect via:
                -> VPN
                -> ExpressRoute (private peering)

    -> Key Points:

        -> Private Endpoint = Private IP for Azure service
        -> Uses Microsoft internal network
        -> Eliminates public internet exposure
        -> Works with firewall rules for strict access control

=> Managed Identity (Azure App Configuration Context)
    -> Purpose:
        -> Used by App Configuration to securely access other Azure services (e.g., Key Vault)
        -> No need to store or manage credentials (client secret/certificate)

    -> Key Usage:
        -> Authenticate with Microsoft Entra ID
        -> Access Key Vault for:
            -> Key wrapping (CMK)
            -> Secret retrieval

    -> Types:
        -> System-Assigned Identity:
            -> Linked to App Configuration instance
            -> Auto-created and deleted with resource
            -> Only one per resource
        -> User-Assigned Identity:
            -> Separate Azure resource
            -> Can be shared across multiple resources
            -> Multiple identities can be assigned

    -> Required for:
        -> Customer-Managed Keys (CMK)
        -> Secure service-to-service communication

    -> Key Point:
        -> Managed Identity = Secure, passwordless authentication mechanism